{"id": "2c867773-3c75-476e-b7e1-04d15eee4139", "timestamp": "2026-05-28T13:20:53.303611", "source": "agent", "thought": [{"cache_prompt": false, "type": "text", "text": "I see the issue now. The generated code has `and tokenize lexbuf lexbuf` - it's duplicating the lexbuf parameter. This is a bug in how FsLexYacc generates the code. The issue is that when we define `rule tokenize lexbuf = parse`, the FsLexYacc tool is adding the lexbuf parameter automatically AND we're also adding it explicitly.\n\nLet me look at the original Lexer.fsl to understand the correct syntax:\n\n"}], "reasoning_content": null, "thinking_blocks": [], "responses_reasoning_item": null, "action": {"command": "cat Lexer.fsl", "is_input": false, "timeout": null, "reset": false, "kind": "TerminalAction"}, "tool_name": "terminal", "tool_call_id": "43768dbb-09f1-4c87-b4d9-da5b21b0bf4b", "tool_call": {"id": "43768dbb-09f1-4c87-b4d9-da5b21b0bf4b", "responses_item_id": null, "name": "terminal", "arguments": "{\"command\": \"cat Lexer.fsl\", \"security_risk\": \"LOW\", \"summary\": \"View current Lexer.fsl content\"}", "origin": "completion"}, "llm_response_id": "chatcmpl-2a55493a-eb55-4ddc-b7bd-b88322747c48", "security_risk": "LOW", "critic_result": null, "summary": "View current Lexer.fsl content", "kind": "ActionEvent"}
{"id": "21b37ef5-9c4a-42df-9d69-e36ae2ce1720", "timestamp": "2026-05-28T13:20:53.524164", "source": "environment", "tool_name": "terminal", "tool_call_id": "43768dbb-09f1-4c87-b4d9-da5b21b0bf4b", "observation": {"content": [{"cache_prompt": false, "type": "text", "text": "{\nopen Parser\nopen FSharp.Text.Lexing\n\nexception LexingError of string\n}\n\nrule tokenize lexbuf = parse\n  | [' ' '\\t'] { tokenize lexbuf }\n  | ['0'-'9']+ { INT (int (Lexing.matched lexbuf)) }\n  | '+' { PLUS }\n  | '-' { MINUS }\n  | '*' { STAR }\n  | '/' { SLASH }\n  | '(' { LPAREN }\n  | ')' { RPAREN }\n  | eof { EOF }\n  | _ { raise (LexingError (sprintf \"Unexpected character: %c\" (lexbuf.LexemeChar 0))) }"}], "is_error": false, "command": "cat Lexer.fsl", "exit_code": 0, "timeout": false, "metadata": {"exit_code": 0, "pid": -1, "username": "ohama", "hostname": "ohama", "working_dir": "/Users/ohama/projs/OpenHandsTests/oh-workdir-122b/calc", "py_interpreter_path": "", "prefix": "", "suffix": "\n[The command completed with exit code 0.]"}, "full_output_save_dir": "/Users/ohama/.openhands/conversations/cc5ecd888c3444239a2d24bfe0a9005c/observations", "kind": "TerminalObservation"}, "action_id": "2c867773-3c75-476e-b7e1-04d15eee4139", "kind": "ObservationEvent"}
{"id": "ba3974da-d797-4134-aad5-5d2cc54d03ce", "timestamp": "2026-05-28T13:21:22.213524", "source": "agent", "thought": [{"cache_prompt": false, "type": "text", "text": "The issue is that FsLexYacc automatically adds the `lexbuf` parameter to rule functions. When we write `rule tokenize lexbuf = parse`, it generates `tokenize lexbuf lexbuf` (double lexbuf). The correct syntax is to just write `rule tokenize = parse` and let FsLexYacc handle the lexbuf parameter automatically.\n\nBut the original file had `rule tokenize = parse` and the recursive call was `tokenize` without lexbuf. The problem is that the generated code expects the function to take a lexbuf parameter. Let me check the FsLexYacc documentation by looking at how it should work:\n\n"}], "reasoning_content": null, "thinking_blocks": [], "responses_reasoning_item": null, "action": {"thought": "\nLooking at the generated code, I see:\n```\nand tokenize lexbuf lexbuf =\n```\n\nThis is clearly a bug - the lexbuf is being duplicated. The issue is that when I wrote `rule tokenize lexbuf = parse`, the FsLexYacc tool is adding lexbuf automatically AND I also specified it.\n\nThe correct FsLexYacc syntax for a rule is:\n```\nrule tokenize = parse\n```\n\nAnd when you call it recursively, you should just call `tokenize` without any arguments - the tool generates the proper function signature.\n\nBut wait, the original file had:\n```\nrule tokenize = parse\n  | [' ' '\\t'] { tokenize }\n```\n\nAnd the error was:\n```\nerror FS0001: \ud615\uc2dd\uc774 \uc77c\uce58\ud558\uc9c0 \uc54a\uc2b5\ub2c8\ub2e4.    ''a'\uc774(\uac00)    \ud544\uc694\ud558\uc9c0\ub9cc    'LexBuffer<char> -> 'a'\uc774(\uac00) \uc9c0\uc815\ub418\uc5c8\uc2b5\ub2c8\ub2e4.\n```\n\nThis means the type expected is something different. The issue is that when the lexer generates the function, it needs to return a token, but `tokenize` (without arguments) returns a function `LexBuffer<char> -> token`.\n\nLet me look at the generated code more carefully. T